# Apple Human Interface Guidelines (HIG) - iOS/SwiftUI

## Core Design Principles

### Visual Hierarchy & Clarity
- Use visual weight, size, and placement to show element importance
- Leading content is most important; trailing content secondary
- Group related elements; separate unrelated ones
- Use whitespace generously for breathing room

### Materials & Depth (iOS 18+)
- Use `.ultraThinMaterial`, `.thinMaterial`, `.regularMaterial`, `.thickMaterial` for layering
- Standard materials: Help with visual differentiation in content layer
- Materials create sense of depth between foreground and background

### Liquid Glass (iOS 26+ / WWDC 2025)
Source: https://developer.apple.com/documentation/TechnologyOverviews/adopting-liquid-glass

Liquid Glass is Apple's new unified design language across all platforms:

**Core Principles:**
- Dynamic translucency that adapts to background content
- Unified control appearance across navigation, toolbars, tabs
- Automatic adoption for system controls (TabView, NavigationStack, sheets)
- Preserves content visibility while providing clear UI hierarchy

**SwiftUI Modifiers (iOS 26+):**
```swift
// Apply glass effect to custom views
.glassEffect()                          // Default glass appearance
.glassEffect(.regular)                  // Standard glass intensity
.glassEffect(.prominent)                // More visible glass
.glassEffect(.regular.interactive())    // Interactive glass (buttons)

// Glass effect container for grouping
GlassEffectContainer {
    // Child views share glass background
}

// Control glass behavior
.glassEffectUnion(id: "myGroup")        // Group multiple glass elements
.glassEffectDisabled()                  // Opt out of automatic glass
```

**Automatic Adoption:**
- TabView → glass tab bar automatically
- NavigationStack → glass navigation bar
- .sheet() / .fullScreenCover() → glass modal chrome
- ToolbarItem → glass toolbar buttons

**Backwards Compatibility:**
- On iOS 18 and earlier: falls back to `.ultraThinMaterial` + blur
- Use `if #available(iOS 26, *)` for conditional glass features
- Standard materials (`.thinMaterial`, etc.) still work everywhere

**Best Practices:**
- Let system controls adopt glass automatically
- Use `.glassEffect()` for custom floating UI elements
- Avoid mixing glass with opaque backgrounds
- Test on both light and dark backgrounds for readability
- Glass works best on dynamic/photo content backgrounds

### Dark Mode
- Use semantic system colors: `.systemBackground`, `.secondarySystemBackground`
- iOS uses base (dimmer) and elevated (brighter) backgrounds for depth perception
- System automatically shifts colors based on context (popover, modal, multitasking)
- Never use pure black/white; prefer system colors

### Typography
- Use Dynamic Type sizes: `.largeTitle`, `.title`, `.headline`, `.body`, `.caption`
- SF Pro is the system font; avoid custom fonts unless brand-specific
- Bold for emphasis, regular for body text
- Minimum touch target: 44x44 points

### Spacing & Layout
- Use standard spacing: 4, 8, 12, 16, 20, 24, 32 points
- Safe Area: Always respect `safeAreaInsets`
- Padding: 16pt horizontal padding for content
- Card spacing: 12-16pt between cards

### Color
- Use semantic colors: `.primary`, `.secondary`, `.accent`
- Accent color should be consistent throughout app
- High contrast for important elements
- Vibrant colors for labels on materials: `.label`, `.secondaryLabel`, `.tertiaryLabel`

### Iconography
- Use SF Symbols (2000+ icons)
- Match icon weight to text weight
- Use `.fill` variants for selected states
- Standard sizes: 12, 14, 16, 20, 24, 28 points

### Animation & Motion
- Use `.spring(response:, dampingFraction:)` for natural feel
- `.easeInOut` for state changes
- Duration: 0.2-0.4s for most transitions
- Match system animation curves

### Touch & Interaction
- Minimum touch target: 44x44 points
- Provide haptic feedback for important actions
- Use `buttonStyle(.plain)` for custom buttons
- Avoid gestures that conflict with system gestures

### Accessibility
- Support Dynamic Type
- Ensure 4.5:1 contrast ratio for text
- Add accessibility labels to all interactive elements
- Support VoiceOver
- Test with reduced motion enabled

## SwiftUI Best Practices

### Materials Example
```swift
.background(.ultraThinMaterial)
.background(.regularMaterial, in: RoundedRectangle(cornerRadius: 16))
```

### Dark Mode Colors
```swift
Color(.systemBackground)           // Primary background
Color(.secondarySystemBackground)  // Cards, grouped content
Color(.tertiarySystemBackground)   // Nested elements
```

### Typography Scale
```swift
.font(.largeTitle)    // 34pt - Screen titles
.font(.title)         // 28pt - Section headers  
.font(.title2)        // 22pt - Subsection headers
.font(.headline)      // 17pt bold - Cell headers
.font(.body)          // 17pt - Primary content
.font(.callout)       // 16pt - Secondary content
.font(.subheadline)   // 15pt - Tertiary content
.font(.footnote)      // 13pt - Captions
.font(.caption)       // 12pt - Labels
.font(.caption2)      // 11pt - Small labels
```

### Haptic Feedback
```swift
UIImpactFeedbackGenerator(style: .light).impactOccurred()
UIImpactFeedbackGenerator(style: .medium).impactOccurred()
UINotificationFeedbackGenerator().notificationOccurred(.success)
```

### SF Symbols Usage
```swift
Image(systemName: "shield.checkered")
    .font(.title2.weight(.semibold))
    .foregroundStyle(.primary)
    .symbolRenderingMode(.hierarchical)
```

### Liquid Glass Examples (iOS 26+)
```swift
// Custom floating action button with glass
Button(action: {}) {
    Image(systemName: "plus")
        .font(.title2)
}
.frame(width: 56, height: 56)
.glassEffect(.regular.interactive())

// Floating card with glass background
VStack {
    Text("Status Card")
    Text("Active")
}
.padding()
.glassEffect()
.clipShape(RoundedRectangle(cornerRadius: 20))

// Grouped glass elements (share same background)
GlassEffectContainer {
    HStack {
        Button("Left") {}
        Button("Right") {}
    }
}

// Fallback for iOS 18 and earlier
@ViewBuilder
func adaptiveGlass<Content: View>(@ViewBuilder content: () -> Content) -> some View {
    if #available(iOS 26, *) {
        content().glassEffect()
    } else {
        content()
            .background(.ultraThinMaterial)
            .clipShape(RoundedRectangle(cornerRadius: 16))
    }
}
```

## Don'ts
- Don't use pure #000000 or #FFFFFF
- Don't ignore safe areas
- Don't make touch targets smaller than 44pt
- Don't use low-contrast text
- Don't fight system gestures
- Don't disable animations for all users
- Don't hardcode colors; use semantic colors

### Liquid Glass Don'ts (iOS 26+)
- Don't put glass on solid color backgrounds (defeats the purpose)
- Don't nest multiple glass layers (visual noise)
- Don't use `.glassEffect()` on every element (overwhelming)
- Don't mix glass with heavy shadows (conflicts visually)
- Don't forget to test glass on various background images/colors
- Don't use glass for content that needs guaranteed legibility (use solid backgrounds)
